=========================================================
C++ TEMPLATES – COMPLETE INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================================

*******What are Templates?
-------------------
Templates allow writing generic (type-independent) code.

Instead of writing separate functions/classes for int, float, string, etc.,
we write one template that works for any type.

Benefits:
✓ Code reuse
✓ Type safety
✓ Compile-time polymorphism  **********
✓ Better performance (no runtime overhead) **********

*******Why are template definitions usually in header files? ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Templates are instantiated at compile time. The compiler must see the complete template
definition whenever it generates code for a specific type.

Template definitions are typically placed in header files because the compiler needs the full definition 
at the point of instantiation. Unlike normal functions, templates are instantiated during compilation, so hiding the implementation 
in a .cpp file usually results in linker errors unless explicit instantiations are provided.

Code Bloat ⭐⭐⭐⭐

Interviewers often ask:

*********What is one disadvantage of templates?
Every type creates a separate instantiation.
maximum<int>()

maximum<double>()

maximum<float>()

Compiler generates
int maximum(...)

double maximum(...)

float maximum(...)
More generated code can increase executable size.

This is called Code Bloat.

***Implicit vs Explicit Instantiation ⭐⭐⭐⭐
Implicit
Box<int> b;
Compiler automatically generates Box<int>.

Explicit
template class Box<int>;
You explicitly ask the compiler to instantiate it, even if it's not used.


=========================================================
1. Function Template ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
=========================================================

Syntax:

template<typename T>
return_type function_name(parameters)

Example:

template<typename T>
T maximum(T a, T b)
{
    return (a > b) ? a : b;
}

Usage:

cout << maximum(10,20);
cout << maximum(3.5,4.8);
cout << maximum('A','B');

Compiler generates separate functions for each type.

