7. Template Specialization ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ (VERY IMPORTANT)
=========================================================

What is Template Specialization?
--------------------------------

Template Specialization allows us to provide a custom implementation
for a specific data type while keeping the generic implementation
for all other types.

Think of it as saying:

"Normally use the generic template,
but if the type is X, use this special implementation."

---------------------------------------------------------
Why do we need Template Specialization?
---------------------------------------------------------

Suppose we have a generic Printer class.

template<typename T>
class Printer
{
public:
    void print()
    {
        cout << "Generic Printer";
    }
};

This works for all types.

But suppose we want char to print differently.

Example:

Printer<int>      -> Generic Printer
Printer<double>   -> Generic Printer
Printer<char>     -> Character Printer

Generic code cannot satisfy this requirement.

Hence we specialize it.

---------------------------------------------------------
Example
---------------------------------------------------------

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

template<typename T>
class Printer
{
public:
    void print()
    {
        cout << "Generic Printer" << endl;
    }
};

template<>
class Printer<char>
{
public:
    void print()
    {
        cout << "Character Printer" << endl;
    }
};

int main()
{
    Printer<int> p1;
    Printer<double> p2;
    Printer<char> p3;

    p1.print();
    p2.print();
    p3.print();
}

Output:

Generic Printer
Generic Printer
Character Printer

---------------------------------------------------------
What happens internally?
---------------------------------------------------------

Compiler sees:

Printer<int>

No specialization exists.

Uses generic template.

---------------------------------------------------------

Compiler sees:

Printer<double>

No specialization exists.

Uses generic template.

---------------------------------------------------------

Compiler sees:

Printer<char>

Compiler finds

template<>
class Printer<char>

Uses specialized version.

---------------------------------------------------------
Flow
---------------------------------------------------------

Printer<int>
      │
      ▼
Specialization available?
      │
      ├── No
      ▼
Generic Template

-----------------------------------------

Printer<char>
      │
      ▼
Specialization available?
      │
      ├── Yes
      ▼
Specialized Template

---------------------------------------------------------
Function Template Specialization
---------------------------------------------------------

template<typename T>
void show(T x)
{
    cout << "Generic" << endl;
}

template<>
void show<char>(char x)
{
    cout << "Character" << endl;
}

Usage:

show(10);

Output:

Generic

----------------------------

show('A');

Output:

Character

---------------------------------------------------------
Real World Example
---------------------------------------------------------

Suppose generic comparison:

template<typename T>
bool compare(T a, T b)
{
    return a == b;
}

Works for:

int

double

float

But for C-style strings:

compare("ABC","ABC")

Generic version compares addresses.

Wrong!

Need specialization.

template<>
bool compare<const char*>(const char* a,
                          const char* b)
{
    return strcmp(a,b)==0;
}

Now actual string contents are compared.

This is a very common interview example.

---------------------------------------------------------
Advantages
---------------------------------------------------------

✓ Handle special cases

✓ Reuse generic implementation

✓ Improve performance

✓ Customize behavior for particular types

---------------------------------------------------------
Disadvantages
---------------------------------------------------------

✗ More code to maintain

✗ Too many specializations reduce readability

---------------------------------------------------------
Important Rules
---------------------------------------------------------

1. Generic template must exist first.

2. Specialization must exactly match the type.

Correct:

template<>
class Printer<char>

Wrong:

template<>
class Printer<int*>

unless specifically required.

3. Compiler prefers specialization over generic template.

---------------------------------------------------------
Template Specialization vs Overloading
---------------------------------------------------------

Overloading

Different parameter list.

Example

void print(int);

void print(double);

-------------------------------------

Specialization

Same template

Different implementation for specific type.

Example

Printer<T>

Printer<char>

---------------------------------------------------------
Template Specialization vs Inheritance
---------------------------------------------------------

Inheritance changes behavior through runtime polymorphism.

Template specialization changes behavior at compile time.

---------------------------------------------------------
Most Asked Interview Questions
---------------------------------------------------------

Q. What is template specialization?

A.

Template specialization provides a custom implementation
for a particular template argument while keeping
the generic implementation for all other types.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Why do we need template specialization?

Sometimes one type requires completely different behavior.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. When is specialization selected?

At compile time.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Does specialization improve runtime performance?

Yes.

Selection happens during compilation.

No runtime overhead.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Which implementation is chosen?

Compiler first looks for an exact specialization.

If found

↓

Uses specialization.

Else

↓

Uses generic template.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Can we specialize function templates?

Yes.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Can we specialize class templates?

Yes.

---------------------------------------------------------

Interview Answer (30 seconds)
---------------------------------------------------------

"Template specialization allows us to provide a custom implementation
for a specific template type while keeping the generic implementation
for all other types. During compilation, the compiler first checks
whether a specialization exists for the requested type. If it does,
that version is instantiated; otherwise, the generic template is used.
A common real-world example is specializing code for const char*
because generic templates compare pointer addresses rather than string
contents."

