15. Variadic Templates (C++11) ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ (VERY IMPORTANT)
=========================================================

What are Variadic Templates?
----------------------------

Variadic Templates allow a function or class template
to accept ANY number of template arguments.

Before C++11, if we wanted functions with different numbers
of arguments, we had to overload them.

Example:

print(int)

print(int,int)

print(int,int,int)

print(int,int,int,int)

Many overloads were required.

With Variadic Templates,
ONE function handles all cases.

---------------------------------------------------------
Syntax
---------------------------------------------------------

template<typename... Args>

Args...

is called a

Template Parameter Pack

---------------------------------------------------------

Function Parameters

Args... args

args...

is called a

Function Parameter Pack

---------------------------------------------------------
Simple Example
---------------------------------------------------------

template<typename... Args>
void print(Args... args)
{
}

Can accept

print(10);

print(10,20);

print(10,20,30);

print(10,"ABC",3.5);

---------------------------------------------------------
Why do we need Variadic Templates?******************************
---------------------------------------------------------

Without variadic templates

void print(int);

void print(int,int);

void print(int,int,int);

void print(int,int,int,int);

Large amount of duplicate code.

Variadic templates solve this problem.

=========================================================
Example 1 : Recursive Variadic Template ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐*********************
=========================================================

#include<iostream>
using namespace std;

void print()
{
    cout << "End" << endl;
}

template<typename T, typename... Args>
void print(T first, Args... rest)
{
    cout << first << " ";

    print(rest...);
}

int main()
{
    print(10,20,30);

    print("ABC",3.14,'X');
}

Output

10 20 30 End

ABC 3.14 X End

---------------------------------------------------------
How does recursion work?
---------------------------------------------------------

Compiler sees

print(10,20,30);

Step 1

first = 10

rest = 20,30

Calls

print(20,30);

-------------------------------------

Step 2

first = 20

rest = 30

Calls

print(30);

-------------------------------------

Step 3

first = 30

rest = empty

Calls

print();

-------------------------------------

Base function executes

End

---------------------------------------------------------
Visualization
---------------------------------------------------------

print(10,20,30)

↓

10

↓

print(20,30)

↓

20

↓

print(30)

↓

30

↓

print()

↓

End

=========================================================
Example 2 : Count Number of Arguments
=========================================================

#include<iostream>
using namespace std;

template<typename... Args>
void countArgs(Args... args)
{
    cout << sizeof...(Args) << endl;
}

int main()
{
    countArgs();

    countArgs(10);

    countArgs(10,20);

    countArgs(10,20,30,40);
}

Output

0

1

2

4

---------------------------------------------------------
sizeof...(Args)

returns

Number of template arguments.

=========================================================
Example 3 : Mixed Types
=========================================================

print(10,
      3.14,
      'A',
      "Hello",
